    echo "Green!";                  
    $counter = $counter + 30; //stop if triggered
    } 
    elseif (stristr($data,$stringR)) {
    echo "Red";                 
    $counter = $counter + 30;  //stop if triggered
    }
    elseif (stristr($data,$stringB)) {
    echo "Blue";  
    $counter = $counter + 30;  //stop if triggered
    }
    elseif (stristr($data,$stringO)) {
    echo "Orange";  
    $counter = $counter + 30;  //stop if triggered
    }
    else {
    //increment loop counter
    $counter = $counter + 1;
    //Insert pause
    sleep(10);
    }   
    }

?>
```

Answer:
Your question is not completely clear.  I understand it that you want a single line of output for each word in the first file.  In that case, you are doing the output stage inside the wrong loop.  You should do it in the outer loop, not the inner one.  For the inner loop, you just loop until found.

The other problem you have is expecting ```
string::find```
 to return a boolean.  This is not true.  It returns an index, or ```
string::npos```
 if not found.  You could have used the string equality operator instead.

So, using the above recommendations, your code becomes:

```
for(size_t i = 0; i < fileContent.size() ; i++)
{
    bool found = false;
    for(size_t j = 0; j < fileContent1.size() && !found; j++)
    {
        found = fileContent[i] == fileContent1[j];
    }

    if(found) {
        cout << "YES:" << fileContent.at(i) << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "NO:" << fileContent.at(i) << endl;
    }
}
```


Of course, you can avoid the inner loop altogether if you use ```
std::find```
 on the vector.

```
bool found = std::find(fileContent1.begin(), fileContent1.end(), fileContent[i]) != fileContent1.end();
```

